[[File:The Love of Paris and Helen by Jacques-Louis David.jpg|thumb|300px]]
'''''The Loves of Paris and Helen''''' is a 1788 painting by [[Jacques-Louis David]], showing [[Helen of Troy]] and [[Paris (mythology)|Paris]] from [[Homer]]'s ''[[Iliad]]''. It is now in the [[Louvre Museum]].

It was the result of a commission from the [[Charles X of France|comte d'Artois]]. It shows David in his 'galante' phase and was interpreted as a satire on the manners of the comte d'Artois. The [[caryatid]]s in the background are copies of those by [[Jean Goujon]] in the Louvre.

